'''The Wallflowers''' is an American [[rock music|rock]] solo project of American singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist [[Jakob Dylan]].<ref name="Greiving 2021"/> The Wallflowers were originally a [[roots rock]] band formed in [[Los Angeles]] in 1989 by Dylan and guitarist Tobi Miller. The band has gone through a number of personnel changes but has remained centered on Dylan. Members of The Wallflowers have gone on to be in the Foo Fighters, Ozomatli, and Gogol Bordello. Two former members have been inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Search {{!}} Rock & Roll Hall of Fame |url=https://www.rockhall.com/search?q=rami+jaffee |access-date=2022-09-02 |website=www.rockhall.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Search {{!}} Rock & Roll Hall of Fame |url=https://www.rockhall.com/search?q=jack+irons |access-date=2022-09-02 |website=www.rockhall.com}}</ref>

Following their eponymous [[The Wallflowers (album)|debut album]] in 1992, the Wallflowers released what would become their best-known and highest-selling album, ''[[Bringing Down the Horse]]'' (1996), which included the hit songs "[[One Headlight]]," "[[6th Avenue Heartache]]," "[[The Difference (The Wallflowers song)|The Difference]]," and "[[Three Marlenas]]." Their next album, ''[[Breach (The Wallflowers album)|(Breach)]]'' (2000), contained "[[Sleepwalker]]", their first and only single to reach the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] (at number 76). ("One Headlight" was not released as a single in the U.S.)<ref>{{cite magazine| url= https://www.billboard.com/music/the-wallflowers| title= The Wallflowers| magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com | date= | access-date= April 7, 2021}}</ref> The group released an additional two critically acclaimed albums before going on hiatus. In 2012, the Wallflowers reunited to release their sixth studio album, ''[[Glad All Over (The Wallflowers album)|Glad All Over]]''. Nearly ten years later they released their seventh studio album, ''[[Exit Wounds (The Wallflowers album)|Exit Wounds]]'' (2021),  which peaked at  on ''Billboard’s'' Top Album Sales chart at No. 3, making it the band’s highest-charting album yet.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Wallflowers' 'Exit Wounds' Debuts at No. 3 on Billboard's Top Album Sales Chart|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9604753/the-wallflowers-exit-wounds-top-album-sales-chart/|access-date=October 21, 2021}}</ref> As of 2022, The Wallflowers have sold over five million albums.'' <ref>{{Cite web|title=RIAA Charts|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=the+wallflowers#search_section/|access-date=September 1, 2022}}</ref>''

The Wallflowers have won two [[Grammy Award]]s: [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]] for "One Headlight" in 1998. "One Headlight" is also listed at #58 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of the ''100 Greatest Pop Songs''. The Wallflowers have been nominated six times for "Best Rock Song" and "Best Rock Performance."<ref>{{Cite web|title=Grammy Awards|url=https://www.grammy.com/artists/jakob-dylan/3015|access-date=September 1, 2022}}</ref> Billboard named "One Headlight" as the #1 Greatest of All Time Adult Alternative Song.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Zakaria |first=Abu |date=2021-02-18 |title=Greatest of All Time Adult Alternative Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-of-all-time-adult-alternative-songs/ |access-date=2022-09-06 |website=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref>

==History==
===1988–1990: Early history===
The Wallflowers' inception came in 1988/1989 when singer-guitarist [[Jakob Dylan]] called his childhood friend, Tobi Miller, also a guitarist, about starting a band.  Dylan and Miller had been in several bands together in high school but went their separate ways upon graduation.  Dylan had moved to [[New York City]] to go to art school while Miller had started his own band called the 45's.  After the 45's broke up in 1989, Miller regained contact with Dylan and they began forming a new band called the Apples.  Barrie Maguire, who was in the 45's with Miller, joined the band as their bass player.  In 1990, [[Peter Yanowitz]] was added as the drummer.  The final member to join the group was keyboardist [[Rami Jaffee]].  Jaffee was an active member of the [[Los Angeles]] music scene and had been playing with multiple bands in the area.  He met Dylan in 1990 in the Kibitz Room, a bar located in the back of [[Canter's]]; a Jewish deli located on [[Fairfax Avenue]] in Los Angeles.  He had heard the Apples were looking for an organ player and after meeting and talking with Dylan in the Kibitz Room, the two headed for Dylan's car to listen to the band's demo tape.  Jaffee was impressed by the songs and asked to join in on the band's next rehearsal.  After a long rehearsal session, Jaffee joined the band on the spot.<ref>{{cite serial |episode=Rami Jaffee |series=Dean Delray's Let There Be Talk|title=The Wallflowers |network=iTunes |date=2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Who's Who: Rami Jaffee |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/people.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=August 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716035500/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/people.html |archive-date=July 16, 2006 }}</ref>

===1991–1994: Debut album===
The Apples changed their name to the Wallflowers and began playing clubs around Los Angeles, specifically the [[Sunset Strip]], such as the [[Whisky a Go Go]], [[Gazzarri's]] and the [[Viper Room]]. While they were playing clubs the band was also sending their demo tape to record companies and figures within the music industry. One of those tapes caught the attention of Andrew Slater, who would eventually become the Wallflowers' manager.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Fricke |first1=David |title=The Confessions of Jakob Dylan: A Wallflower's Coming Out |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_rs1000.htm |via=The Wallflowers Network |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=June 5, 2014 |archive-date=October 13, 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013150951/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_rs1000.htm }}</ref> Slater brought the Wallflowers to [[Virgin Records]], who signed the band to a record contract. The Wallflowers then set out to make their first album.  However, finding a producer who was willing to work with them proved to be difficult. The band was intent on recording live and few producers were willing to produce that way. Paul Fox eventually stepped in and agreed to produce the album. By the time the Wallflowers got into the studio in 1991, they had a small catalog of songs they had been performing live which they wanted to record for their debut album. All of the songs were written by Dylan with the rest of the band members contributing input on the music. When in the studio, the band were intent on using as little recording equipment as possible.  Dylan explained: "If I could have had it my way I would not have seen a microphone or a cable anywhere."<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflower |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles96_97.html |via=The Wallflowers Network |work=Details Magazine |access-date=June 5, 2014 |date=July 1997 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145453/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles96_97.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref> When it came to recording, the songs were drawn out past the 3 to 4 minute norm; many songs were close to 5 minutes in length with two exceeding 7 minutes. The Wallflowers finished recording and released their [[The Wallflowers (album)|self-titled debut album]] on August 25, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers – The Wallflowers |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-wallflowers-mw0000082675|website=All Music|access-date=October 26, 2014}}</ref> After the release they began touring nationwide as an opening act for bands such as [[Spin Doctors]] and [[10,000 Maniacs]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Calendar Archive: 1992 |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=June 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145030/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>

The Wallflowers continued to tour through the first half of 1993 but despite this sales of the album were slow. In total, 40,000 copies were sold.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrington |first1=Richard |title=Jakob Dylan, Rising Without Trading on his Dad's Fame: A Wallflower Blooms |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article112697.htm |via=The Wallflowers Network |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=June 5, 2014 |archive-date=October 13, 2006 |date=November 26, 1997 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061013150956/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article112697.htm }}</ref> Reviews for the album, however, were mostly positive.  ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the album 4 stars calling it, "one sweet debut" and describing Dylan's songwriting as "impressive."<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Evans |first1=Paul |title=The Wallflowers |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/thewallflowers/albums/album/242641/review/5945676/the_wallflowers |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date= June 5, 2014 |archive-date=November 9, 2007 |date=November 26, 1992 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071109183334/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/thewallflowers/albums/album/242641/review/5945676/the_wallflowers }}</ref> Great reviews notwithstanding, executives at Virgin Records were reportedly not pleased with the album's lack of commercial success.  Around this time, the company was going through a shift in management which led to the removal of [[Jeff Ayeroff]] and Jordan Harris, the two people who initially brought the Wallflowers to Virgin. After Ayeroff and Harris left the company the Wallflowers began to feel that they had no future with Virgin and asked to be released from their contract.  The split with Virgin has been regarded as mutual.<ref>{{cite serial |title=The Truth About That First Record |episode=The Wallflowers |series=iTunes Originals |network=iTunes |date=2005}}</ref> By mid-1993 the Wallflowers were without a record label.

After leaving Virgin, the Wallflowers went back to playing Los Angeles clubs in hopes of getting signed with another label. The band found it difficult to even get label representatives to come to their shows. In the year it took to get another record deal the Wallflowers gained and lost several band members. Bass player Barrie Maguire was asked to leave for undisclosed reasons in early 1993. The Wallflowers continued playing shows with replacement bass player Jimmie Snider until May 1993 when the band hired Greg Richling. Dylan and Richling went to high school together. The Wallflowers continued to play club shows in Los Angeles through early 1994 when drummer Peter Yanowitz left the band to join his girlfriend Natalie Merchant's band. Yanowitz brought in Barrie Maguire to help record Merchant's debut solo album, ''[[Tigerlily]]''. Around the time of Yanowitz's departure the Wallflowers caught the attention of [[Jimmy Iovine]] and Tom Whalley of [[Interscope Records]], who then signed the band to their label in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Who's Who: Barrie Maguire |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/people.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=June 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716035500/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/people.html |archive-date=July 16, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Who's Who: Greg Richling |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/people.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716035500/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/people.html |archive-date=July 16, 2006 }}</ref>

===1995–1998: ''Bringing Down the Horse''===
After signing with Interscope Records, the Wallflowers began preparations for their second album, ''[[Bringing Down the Horse]]''.  They again had trouble finding a producer that was willing to work with them. The Wallflowers began sending demo tapes to producers and one of the tapes landed in the hands of [[T Bone Burnett]].  Burnett was impressed by the songs and agreed to produce the band.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Hirshey |first1=Gerri |title=Jakob's Ladder |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles96_97.html |via=The Wallflowers Network |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=June 5, 2014 |archive-date=October 13, 2006 |date=June 12, 1997 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145453/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles96_97.html }}</ref>  However, just as they were getting ready to record, the band's guitarist Tobi Miller quit.  This left the Wallflowers without a permanent drummer or guitarist while they were in the studio. [[Matt Chamberlain]] filled in on drums throughout the recording sessions and several guitarists were brought in to fill Miller's role including [[Mike Campbell (musician)|Mike Campbell]], [[Fred Tackett]], [[Jay Joyce]] and [[Michael Ward (musician)|Michael Ward]], who would go on to become a permanent member of the Wallflowers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bringing Down the Horse: Credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/bringing-down-the-horse-mw0000175010/credits|publisher=All Music|access-date=June 5, 2014}}</ref>

The Wallflowers released ''Bringing Down the Horse'' on May 21, 1996.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bringing Down the Horse|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/bringing-down-the-horse-mw0000175010|publisher=All Music}}</ref>  The band began touring for the album soon after the release.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Calendar Archive: 1996 |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=June 22, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145030/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  Album sales were slow to start but after the first single, "[[6th Avenue Heartache]]" (featuring [[Adam Duritz]] of [[Counting Crows]]) was released on August 19, interest in the Wallflowers began picking up as the song began getting more radio play.  The [[David Fincher]]-directed music video for "6th Avenue Heartache" was also receiving attention on [[MTV]] and [[VH1]].  The Wallflowers continued to tour through the rest of 1996 and were featured as a musical guest on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' that November.  On December 1, ''Bringing Down the Horse'' received Gold certification from the [[RIAA]] by selling 500,000 copies of their album.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|title=RIAA Gold & Platinum|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Wallflowers&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50|publisher=RIAA}}</ref>

In January 1997, the Wallflowers were nominated for two [[Grammy Award|Grammy awards]], both for "6th Avenue Heartache".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Complete List of Nominees|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-01-08/entertainment/ca-16471_1_video-producer/2|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=June 22, 2014|date=January 8, 1997}}</ref>  Dylan was a presenter at the [[39th Annual Grammy Awards|1997 Grammy Awards]] though he and the Wallflowers did not win either of the awards they were nominated for.

The band continued to tour and gain popularity.  In February 1997, the Wallflowers completed a tour opening for [[Sheryl Crow]] before beginning a string of their own headlining shows beginning at the end of February and running through May.  On February 24, the second single from ''Bringing Down the Horse'', "[[One Headlight]]", was released.  "One Headlight" received heavy radio play, which propelled ''Bringing Down the Horse'' to Platinum certification on March 4 by selling one million copies of the album.  Within six weeks, sales for ''Bringing Down the Horse'' doubled and on April 16, the album received Double-Platinum status by selling two million copies.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  In mid-May, the Wallflowers crossed over to Europe for a three-week-long tour.  Upon return in mid-June, the Wallflowers continued to tour the United States.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|title=The Calendar Archive: 1997 |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |publisher=The Wallflowers Network |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145030/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  On June 12, Dylan received his first [[Rolling Stone|''Rolling Stone'' magazine]] cover.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hirshey |first1=Gerri |title=Jakob's Ladder |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles96_97.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=June 22, 2014 |date=June 12, 1997 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145453/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles96_97.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  In the accompanying interview, Dylan spoke both candidly and at length about his lineage for the first time.  Five days later, album sales for ''Bringing Down the Horse'' reached the three million mark, qualifying the album for Triple-Platinum status.<ref>{{cite web|title=RIAA Gold & Platinum|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Wallflowers&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50|publisher=RIAA|access-date=July 22, 2014}}</ref>  On June 21, the Wallflowers co-headlined a festival at [[Texas Motor Speedway]] called Rock Fest.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Riemenschneider|first1=Chris|title=Doing Some Blockbuster Promotion|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-06-23/entertainment/ca-6103_1_blockbuster-promotion|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 23, 1997}}</ref>  The day-long festival drew upwards of 400,000 people, making it one of the largest concerts in US history.

On July 2, 1997, the Wallflowers kicked off a co-headlining tour with Counting Crows that continued through September.  This tour included opening acts by [[Bettie Serveert]], [[Engine 88]], [[Gigolo Aunts]], and [[That Dog]], with each opening band touring for a three-week stretch.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fA8EAAAAMBAJ&q=Bettie+Serveert+%22The+Wallflowers%22+1997&pg=PA16|magazine=Billboard|access-date=July 5, 2017|pages=16|date=May 24, 1997|title=Birenbaum Exits Discovery; Cash, Nelson Shine on 'Storytellers' Stage|via=Google Books}}</ref>  The Wallflowers took over full-headlining duties for several shows in July when Counting Crows were unable to perform due to Duritz's swollen vocal chords.<ref>{{cite web|title=Counting Crows Counted In Again|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1427546/counting-crows-counted-in-again/|website=MTV.com|access-date=January 15, 2015|date=July 25, 1997}}</ref>  On September 22, the Wallflowers released their third single from ''Bringing Down the Horse'', "[[The Difference (The Wallflowers song)|The Difference]]".  On October 30, ''Bringing Down the Horse'' hit another milestone by receiving Quadruple-Platinum status by selling four million copies.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  After taking the month of October off from touring, the Wallflowers hit the road again in November.  On November 9 and 10, the Wallflowers broke from their headlining tour to open for [[the Rolling Stones]] at [[Dodger Stadium]] in Los Angeles.  Less than a week later, the Wallflowers again broke from their tour to co-headline a private show at an arena in [[San Jose, California]] with [[Bob Dylan]] on November 14.  The Wallflowers continued to tour through the end of December.<ref name=autogenerated2 />  By the end of 1997, ''Bringing Down the Horse'' had become the most played album on rock radio and peaked at Number 4 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] while "One Headlight" had received some 209,000 radio spins across all formats.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nelson |first1=Jim |title=The Wallflowers 1997 Rock Album of the Year: Bringing Down the Horse |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article121997.htm |publisher=The Album Network |access-date=July 1, 2014 |date=December 19, 1997 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013155022/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article121997.htm |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>

On January 6, 1998, the Wallflowers received three Grammy nominations; "One Headlight" and "[[The Difference (The Wallflowers song)|The Difference]]" were both nominated for Best Rock Song while "One Headlight" received an additional nomination for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal.<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Grammy Award Nominations|url=http://edition.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/9801/06/grammys.list/index.html|publisher=CNN|access-date=July 1, 2014|date=January 6, 1998}}</ref>  At the [[40th Annual Grammy Awards|1998 Grammy Award ceremony]] on February 25, the Wallflowers walked away with two Grammy Awards; "One Headlight" won for Best Rock Song as well as Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 1998 Grammy Award Winners|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/26/arts/the-1998-grammy-award-winners.html|work=The New York Times|date=February 26, 1998}}</ref>  Despite the fact that ''Bringing Down the Horse'' was released nearly two years previously, the Wallflowers released an additional single from that album on March 23, "[[Three Marlenas]]".  "Three Marlenas" would be the fourth and final single to be released from ''Bringing Down the Horse''.  By 1998 the Wallflowers had begun declining on the ''Billboard'' charts and receiving fewer spins on the radio.  That changed, however, when the [[Godzilla: The Album|soundtrack]] for the 1998 film ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' was released on May 19.  The Wallflowers had recorded a version of [[David Bowie|David Bowie's]] "[[Heroes (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]" which was chosen as the lead single for the soundtrack.  The album peaked at No. 2 on the ''Billboard 200'' and the Wallflowers' version of "Heroes" received heavy radio play.  Though the Wallflowers did not tour in 1998 they did play a series of one-off shows including the [[Tibetan Freedom Concert]] in June at [[RFK Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] and the [[Bridge School Benefit]] in September in [[Mountain View, California]], which was hosted by [[Neil Young]] and his wife [[Pegi Young|Pegi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Calendar Archive: 1998 |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |publisher=The Wallflowers Network |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145030/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>

===1999–2001: ''(Breach)''===
After taking a five-month break from writing and touring, the Wallflowers set out to make their third album, ''[[(Breach)]]''.  Dylan was very diligent in the songwriting process; he rented a studio near his home and would routinely go there to write songs for the album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hilburn |first1=Robert |title=He's Cool with the Family Legacy |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles00_present.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145435/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles00_present.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  However, Dylan was not satisfied with the first batch of songs he came up with.  He decided to scrap them and start over.  The songs that did make it to the studio were considered to be far more personal than any of the songs the Wallflowers had released in the past.  Dylan explained; "I think all my songs are personal, but I just made them a little more dense before, made 'em real thick so that I didn't feel exposed. A lot of younger writers do that.  Before, I haven't really wanted anybody buying my records looking for information about myself or my family, but at this point, the group has a lot of people buying the records who aren't interested in that, so it gives me more freedom."<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Fall Music Preview: Son Mixed with Clouds |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles00_present.html |via=The Wallflowers Network |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145435/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles00_present.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  By the end of 1999, the Wallflowers were ready to begin recording.  The bulk of the album was recorded at [[Sunset Sound Recorders]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Behind "Breach" |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/behind3b.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013161027/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/behind3b.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  The Wallflowers' longtime manager, Andrew Slater co-produced the album with [[Michael Penn]].  The band took their time in the studio.  Like ''Bringing Down the Horse'', ''(Breach)'' took about eight months to record.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bringing It All Back Home |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_gwa00.htm |via=The Wallflowers Network |work=Guitar World Acoustic |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013153955/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_gwa00.htm |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  ''(Breach)'' also featured an array of guest artists including [[Elvis Costello]], [[Mike Campbell (musician)|Mike Campbell]] and [[Black Francis|Frank Black]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lang |first1=Angela |title=Picking Three Wallflowers |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_checkout00b.htm |website=The Wallflowers Network |publisher=Checkout.com |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013150331/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_checkout00b.htm |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>

Four years after the release of ''Bringing Down the Horse'' in 1996, ''(Breach)'' was released on October 10, 2000.  The album was met with generally positive critical reception but underwhelming sales.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breach – The Wallflowers|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/breach/the-wallflowers|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>  ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave ''(Breach)'' four stars, calling the band "more muscular" than they used to be.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Moon |first1=Tom |title=Breach |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/thewallflowers/albums/album/229025/review/5945534/breach |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512222927/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/thewallflowers/albums/album/229025/review/5945534/breach |archive-date=May 12, 2009 }}</ref>  However, ''(Breach)'' commercially floundered in comparison to its high-selling predecessor.  The album peaked at No. 13 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and took almost a year to receive the Gold certification, which is the highest certification ''(Breach)'' has received to date.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breach – The Wallflowers|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/breach-mw0000099710/awards|website=All Music|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RIAA Gold & Platinum Search|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|publisher=RIAA|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>

A month before the official release of ''(Breach)'', the album was leaked in its entirety to file-sharing giant [[Napster]], where a reported 25 million users had the ability to listen to and download the Wallflowers' third album.  With regard to the impact of leaks for big recording artists, former [[Capitol Records]] senior vice president and general manager, Lou Mann stated: "For the Wallflowers or any major superstar band, the problems are major.  In fact they're Herculean, because people already want it and you don't want to dilute your audience."<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Hara|first1=Jon|title=New Wallflowers Album Is Napsterized a Month Before Release|url=http://impressive.net/archives/fogo/20000911201359.A965@impressive.net|website=Impressive.net|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>  Jakob Dylan also explained his feelings about ''(Breach)'' being leaked: "[Album sales are] one of the ways that we have of making a living really.  It's not about record companies, it's not about people's right to trade, you know, it's also how we put food on the table."<ref>{{cite web|title=KMTT Radio Interview |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_kmtt111800.htm |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013154440/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/article_kmtt111800.htm |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>

Despite the disappointing release, the Wallflowers set out on another tour beginning in early October 2000.  After one show in [[Atlanta]] on October 2, the Wallflowers traveled to [[New York City|New York]] to open for [[the Who]] for four nights at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Calendar Archive |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145030/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/calendarall.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>  Later that month, Jakob Dylan was featured on the cover of ''Rolling Stone'' for a second time. The Wallflowers continued to tour throughout the U.S. through mid-December before heading to Japan in February 2001 for their first tour there.

The Wallflowers covered the [[Bee Gees]]' 1968 hit song "[[I Started a Joke]]" for the 2001 film, ''[[Zoolander]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zoolander – Original Soundtrack|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/zoolander-mw0000014645|website=All Music|access-date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>

The band continued to tour the U.S. for the remainder of 2001 until it was announced in early October that guitarist Michael Ward had left the Wallflowers due to creative differences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wallflowers Part Ways with Guitarist Michael Ward|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1449942/wallflowers-part-ways-with-guitarist-michael-ward/|website=MTV|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>

===2002–2003: ''Red Letter Days''===
In 2001, Jakob Dylan began writing for the Wallflowers' fourth album, ''[[Red Letter Days (album)|Red Letter Days]]''.  Later that year while on tour with [[John Mellencamp]], the band began recording using portable equipment.  Some recording was also done at keyboardist Rami Jaffee's house.<ref>{{cite web|title=Band Q&A |url=http://www.wallflowers.com/noflash/qa.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=September 3, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113143043/http://www.wallflowers.com/noflash/qa.html |archive-date=November 13, 2006 }}</ref>  Once the band was finished touring for the year they began recording the bulk of the new record at Jackson Browne's studio in [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]].  By the time the Wallflowers had gotten into Browne's studio, Michael Ward had left the band, leaving them without a lead guitarist for the recording process.  Dylan took on much of the lead guitar duties with [[Mike McCready]], [[Rusty Anderson]] and [[Val McCallum]] also contributing on guitar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Red Letter Days credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/red-letter-days-mw0000024785/credits|website=All Music|access-date=September 3, 2014}}</ref>  Moe Z M.D., who had been touring with Mellencamp, contributed additional percussion and background vocals to the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Red Letter Days|url=http://www.thewallflowers.com/releases/red-letter-days/|website=TheWallflowers.com|access-date=September 10, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208070404/http://www.thewallflowers.com/releases/red-letter-days/|archive-date=February 8, 2013}}</ref> ''Red Letter Days'' was produced by founding Wallflowers member Tobi Miller along with Bill Appleberry.  Recording continued through the new year and was completed on April 12, 2002.  The album was mixed by [[Tom Lord-Alge]], who had mixed the band's previous two albums.  Mixing was completed on May 15, 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Album News |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/behind4.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=September 3, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145559/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/behind4.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>

While the Wallflowers were working on ''Red Letter Days'', they recorded a cover of [[the Beatles]]' 1965 song "[[I'm Looking Through You]]" for the soundtrack to the 2001 film ''[[I Am Sam]]''.  The soundtrack was released on January 8, 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=I Am Sam – Original Soundtrack|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-am-sam-mw0000211379|website=All Music|access-date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>

The first single from the ''Red Letter Days'', "When You're On Top," was released to radio on August 16, 2002.  A music video directed by [[Marc Webb]] followed.  After a few false starts, ''Red Letter Days'' was released on November 5, 2002.  The album was met with mixed to positive reviews.  Many critics noted the harder rock sound and catchy melodies used throughout the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reviews for Red Letter Days|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/red-letter-days/the-wallflowers|website=Metacritic|access-date=September 10, 2014}}</ref>  Commercial performance was relatively mixed as well, peaking at No.32 on the ''Billboard 200''.  Around the time of ''Red Letter Days''' release the Wallflowers embarked on a monthlong U.S. tour stretching into early December.  After another U.S. tour in January 2003, the Wallflowers toured in several European countries in February including [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Germany]] and [[Great Britain]].  After this tour, the Wallflowers' drummer since 1995, [[Mario Calire]] announced he was parting ways with the band.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Flans|first1=Robyn|title=Ozomatli|url=http://www.moderndrummer.com/site/2007/10/ozomatli/#_|website=Modern Drummer|access-date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>

In 2003, the Wallflowers were featured on the soundtrack for the film ''[[American Wedding]]''.  The band recorded a cover of [[Van Morrison]]'s 1970 song "[[Into the Mystic]]".  The film's music department weren't able to secure the licensing rights to use Morrison's version so they enlisted the Wallflowers to cover the song.  Both versions of the song were, however, featured in the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Wedding – Original Soundtrack|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/american-wedding-mw0000038142|website=All Music|access-date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>

===2004–2005: ''Rebel, Sweetheart''===
In July 2004, the Wallflowers returned to the studio to record their fifth album, ''[[Rebel, Sweetheart]]''. This time the band decided to record in [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]], which is where their producer for this album, [[Brendan O'Brien (record producer)|Brendan O'Brien]], is based. O'Brien also contributed on guitar. Fred Eltringham joined the Wallflowers as their new drummer. Jakob Dylan wrote the songs, of which keyboardist Rami Jaffee has said: "What I did notice is that kind of upbeat song with some pretty scary lyrics."<ref>{{cite web|title='Rebel' Wallflower |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles05_rs.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |access-date=October 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013145446/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles05_rs.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Set to Release Rebel, Sweetheart on May 24|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-wallflowers-set-to-release-rebel-sweetheart-on-may-24-54128692.html|website=PR Newswire|access-date=November 13, 2014}}</ref> Dylan painted the album's cover art himself.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rebel, Sweetheart credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/rebel-sweetheart-mw0000257535/credits|website=All Music|access-date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>

On October 14, 2004, the [[Warren Zevon]] tribute album ''[[Enjoy Every Sandwich: The Songs of Warren Zevon]]'' was released, on which the Wallflowers covered Zevon's 1978 song "[[Lawyers, Guns and Money]]."<ref>{{cite web|title=Enjoy Every Sandwich: The Songs of Warren Zevon|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/enjoy-every-sandwich-the-songs-of-warren-zevon-mw0000395539|website=All Music|access-date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> In promotion of the album, the Wallflowers performed "Lawyers, Guns and Money" on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' with Zevon's son, [[Jordan Zevon|Jordan]], on October 12, 2004.

On October 31, 2004, the Wallflowers were flown via military transport plane to the [[USS John C. Stennis (CVN-74)|USS John C. Stennis]] aircraft carrier in the middle of the [[Pacific Ocean]] to perform for the returning troops.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Bring Halloween Treat to Thousands on Aircraft Carrier |url=http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles/article110104.html |website=The Wallflowers Network |publisher=PR Newswire |access-date=October 9, 2014 |date=November 1, 2004 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013151545/http://www.the-wallflowers.net/articles/article110104.html |archive-date=October 13, 2006 }}</ref>

''Rebel, Sweetheart'' was released on May 24, 2005, and was met with positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reviews for Rebel, Sweetheart|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/rebel-sweetheart/the-wallflowers|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> Despite widespread critical acclaim, ''Rebel, Sweetheart'' performed relatively poorly commercially, peaking at No. 40 on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rebel, Sweetheart – The Wallflowers|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/rebel-sweetheart-mw0000257535/awards|website=All Music|access-date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> However, the first single from the album, "The Beautiful Side of Somewhere", hit No. 5 on AAA radio. The second single was "God Says Nothing Back". This was the first Wallflowers album to be released on [[DualDisc]]. On one side was the album, and on the other was a DVD that included exclusive performances and arrangements of some of the band's songs, as well as an interview with comedian [[Jon Lovitz]]. In promotion of the album, the Wallflowers did concerts for the Oxygen Custom Concert Series and [[PBS]] [[Soundstage (TV series)|''Soundstage'']]. Around the time of the album's release, the band set out on what would be their last tour for two years. They were joined by Stuart Mathis on lead guitar. After 2005, the Wallflowers ended their relationship with Interscope Records.

===2006–2010: Hiatus===
[[File:Jakob Dylan Bumbershoot (2822067305).jpg|thumb|The band performing at Bumbershoot in Seattle, Washington on August 31, 2008.]]
2006 was the first year in over a decade that the Wallflowers did not tour. Instead, band members embarked on other projects. Jakob Dylan toured with former Wallflowers producer [[T-Bone Burnett]] in the early summer, performing a solo acoustic opening set with a keyboard player. Later that year, he signed a contract with [[Columbia Records]] as a solo artist. He also wrote and recorded a song called "Here Comes Now", which was featured as the theme song for the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television drama ''[[Six Degrees (TV series)|Six Degrees]]''. The show premiered in the fall of 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jakob Dylan Joins Columbia, Writes for TV|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/57191/jakob-dylan-joins-columbia-writes-for-tv|website=Billboard.com|access-date=October 15, 2014|date=September 20, 2006}}</ref> Meanwhile, keyboardist Rami Jaffee joined the [[Foo Fighters]] as a touring and session member. Jaffee had previously contributed keyboards to the Foo Fighters' 2005 album ''[[In Your Honor]]''. In 2006, he also contributed on albums for [[Willie Nile]] and [[Pete Yorn]].

On August 31, 2007, the Wallflowers announced they would be touring for the first time in over two years. They toured in the Midwest and Northeastern U.S. in October and November. Before the tour, Jaffee announced that he was leaving the Wallflowers. This left Dylan, Greg Richling and Fred Eltringham as the remaining members and a guitar player, Stuart Mathis, as a touring member. In 2008, the Wallflowers toured on-and-off throughout the summer. Touring for the Wallflowers was limited as Dylan had released his first solo album, ''[[Seeing Things (album)|Seeing Things]]'', on June 10, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seeing Things – Jakob Dylan|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/seeing-things-mw0000787005|website=All Music|access-date=October 15, 2014}}</ref> Eltringham joined Dylan on tour in promotion for the album.

On March 31, 2009, the Wallflowers released a greatest-hits album called ''Collected: 1996–2005''. The album featured every single released from the four albums the Wallflowers released between 1996 and 2005. It also featured several non-single songs from those four albums, a demo version of "God Says Nothing Back" and an unreleased song called "Eat You Sleeping".<ref>{{cite web|title=Collected: 1996–2005|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/collected-1996-2005-mw0001466224|website=All Music|access-date=October 15, 2014}}</ref> That summer, the Wallflowers embarked on a U.S. tour in support of the album. In addition to Dylan, Richling, Eltringham and Mathis, Bill Appleberry joined the band on this tour as a keyboard player. The Wallflowers did not tour in 2010 as Dylan had released his second solo album, ''[[Women + Country]]'', on April 6, 2010, and was touring in support of that album.

===2011–2012: ''Glad All Over''===
[[File:The Wallflowers - 8414467152.jpg|thumb|alt=The band onstage in blue light|The Wallflowers in 2012.]]
On November 1, 2011, Jakob Dylan announced that the Wallflowers would be reuniting to release an album, explaining: "I never suggested we were breaking up.  We all felt we were losing the plot a bit and we needed a break.  And that year break becomes two years, then becomes three years, and before you know it five or six years go by pretty quickly.  I can't do what I do in the Wallflowers without them.  I miss it."<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Appleford|first1=Steve|title=Jakob Dylan Planning Wallflowers Reunion|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/jakob-dylan-planning-wallflowers-reunion-20111101|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=October 20, 2014|date=November 1, 2011}}</ref>  In an interview with the ''[[St. Joseph News-Press]]'', Dylan stated that the Wallflowers would be getting into the studio in January and the lineup would include Greg Richling on bass, Rami Jaffee on keys, Stuart Mathis on guitar and Fred Eltringham on drums.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krauskopf|first1=Kevin|title=Jakob Dylan talks Wallflowers reunion|url=http://www.newspressnow.com/life/st_joe_live/article_b095c3a9-797e-5123-9751-cd096fa7c3ab.html?mode=jqm|website=News Press Now|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>  However, weeks before the Wallflowers began recording, Eltringham left the band to pursue other projects.  The band quickly got former [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] and [[Pearl Jam]] drummer [[Jack Irons]] to join the band.  Irons was previously involved in a side project with Wallflowers bassist Richling.

On January 20, 2012, the Wallflowers began recording their sixth studio album, ''[[Glad All Over (The Wallflowers album)|Glad All Over]],'' at [[the Black Keys]]' [[Dan Auerbach]]'s Easy Eye studio in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Glad All Over – The Wallflowers|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/glad-all-over-mw0002407780|website=All Music|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Jay Joyce]], who had played guitar on the Wallflowers' ''Bringing Down the Horse'' agreed to produce the album.  Before going to the studio, the band had decided have a more collaborative writing process than they had in the past.  Instead of Dylan bringing in fully completed songs like he had done in the past, he only brought lyrics.  Dylan and the rest of the band wrote the music for the songs together in the studio.  Joyce explained: "Jakob came to Nashville and we sat down and I asked him to play me a song, but instead he pulled out this 2-inch-thick notebook. ‘This is what I’ve got. Let’s play some grooves and throw it around.’ I thought, ‘Wow, that’s kind of scary, but it’s exciting.’ So we didn't really know going in what we were going to do. We had no songs, no demos. It was all developed in the studio.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Blair|title=The Wallflowers|url=http://mixonline.com/news/profiles/wallflowers/366367|website=Mix|access-date=October 20, 2014|date=October 1, 2012}}</ref>  The band finished recording on February 20, 2012.

At a private solo performance in New York on April 19, 2012, Dylan announced that the new the Wallflowers album was expected to be released in fall later that year.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Duffy|first1=Thom|title=Jakob Dylan Plays Farm Aid Event, Says New Wallflowers Album On the Wya|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/backbeat/1097603/backbeat-jakob-dylan-plays-farm-aid-event-says-new-wallflowers-album|magazine=Billboard|access-date=October 20, 2014|date=April 24, 2012}}</ref> On July 14, 2012, the band announced that the title of their new album would be ''Glad All Over''. They also announced that the album's first single, "Reboot the Mission", would be available for free download from their website.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Return with New Album Glad All Over|url=http://www.jambands.com/news/2012/07/14/the-wallflowers-return-with-new-album-glad-all-over|website=JamBands.com|date=July 14, 2012|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>

Following several one-off shows in the summer of 2012, the Wallflowers kicked off a fall tour in [[San Diego]] on September 8, 2012. From there, they continued to tour the U.S. and Canada through mid-November, playing a mix of clubs and festivals, with an additional four East Coast dates at the end of December.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Concert Setlists & Tour Dates|url=http://www.setlist.fm/setlists/the-wallflowers-7bd6b60c.html?page=7|website=Setlist.fm|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref> ''Glad All Over'' was released on October 9, 2012, on [[Columbia Records]] and was met with generally positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers – Glad All Over|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/glad-all-over-mw0002407780|website=All Music|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Reviews for Glad All Over by The Wallflowers|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/glad-all-over/the-wallflowers|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref> Leading up to the album's release, the Wallflowers promoted the album on various television shows including ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'', the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' and ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show|Ellen]]''.

===2013–2020: Tours and roster changes===
[[File:The Wallflowers - 2014 - Minnesota.JPG|thumb|The Wallflowers perform in Walker, Minnesota on July 19, 2014, with current lineup]]
Beginning in the spring of 2013, the band toured with [[Eric Clapton]] on his arena tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallflowers Announce Spring 2013 Tour with Eric Clapton|url=http://www.thewallflowers.com/2012/11/19/the-wallflowers-announce-2013-spring-tour-with-eric-clapton/|website=TheWallflowers.com|access-date=October 20, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820195705/http://www.thewallflowers.com/2012/11/19/the-wallflowers-announce-2013-spring-tour-with-eric-clapton/|archive-date=August 20, 2014}}</ref> The tour with Clapton began on March 14, 2013, in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], at the [[US Airways Center]] and continued through the South and East Coast, eventually coming to an end on April 6, 2013, in [[Pittsburgh]] at the [[Consol Energy Center]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Derrough|first1=Leslie Michele|title=Eric Clapton/The Wallflowers: New Orleans|url=http://www.glidemagazine.com/22996/eric-clapton-the-wallflowers/|website=Glide Magazine|access-date=October 20, 2014|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Von Bader|first1=David|title=Eric Clapton – Hard Rock Live, Hollywood – March 29|url=http://blogs.browardpalmbeach.com/countygrind/2013/04/eric_clapton_not_ready.php|website=Broward/Palm Beach New Times|access-date=October 20, 2014|date=April 1, 2013}}</ref>

After the Clapton tour, the Wallflowers played several additional shows of their own in May 2013. On May 12 in [[Napa County, California|Napa, California]], the band's longtime keyboardist Rami Jaffee played what would be his final show with the Wallflowers to date. Jaffee has yet to say whether he has officially quit the Wallflowers but has continued to record and tour with the [[Foo Fighters]]. Jimmy Wallace has subbed in his spot ever since.  The Wallflowers continued to tour through the summer of 2013 and played their final show of the summer on August 17 at the River Roots Live Festival in [[Davenport, Iowa]], to a crowd of 17,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Behind the Scenes at River Roots Live 2013|url=http://roadtips.typepad.com/a_salesguys_guide_to_the_/2013/09/behind-the-scenes-at-river-roots-live-2013.html|website=Road Tips|access-date=October 20, 2014}}</ref> This show would turn out to be longtime bassist Greg Richling's and drummer Jack Irons' final show with the band. On September 8, Richling officially announced that he was leaving the Wallflowers after 20 years with the band. He left to pursue other interests. Irons announced he was leaving soon after, on September 15. Irons reportedly left to focus on his band project, Arthur Channel, who released their debut album on October 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yeatts|first1=Andrianna|title=Song Premiere: Arthur Channel|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2013/09/song-premiere-arthur-channel-16-children/|website=American Songwriter|access-date=October 20, 2014|date=September 25, 2013}}</ref>

The Wallflowers have continued to play shows since 2013 with a new drummer, bass player, guitar player, and keyboardist filling in for Irons, Richling, Mathis, and Jaffee.<ref name="Hamad 2016">{{cite web | last=Hamad | first=Michael | title=Jakob Dylan's Wallflowers Still Connecting With Classics | website=courant.com | date=August 23, 2016 | url=https://www.courant.com/ctnow/music/hc-wallflowers-toyota-oakdale-theatre-wallingford-20160822-story.html | access-date=March 25, 2021}}</ref> Dylan stated later he would be continuing making music under name The Wallflowers as a solo project: "The Wallflowers is me, and if I go under my own name, it's me. It's the same thing, ultimately. It's really dictated on the songs I have and how I want to record them and would they sound better with a full-band sound. In many ways it's the same person. It's just what outfit do I want to put on".<ref name="Rs 2016"/> As of 2017, the touring lineup consisted of Stanton Adcock on lead guitar, Steve Mackey on bass, keyboardist Jimmy Wallace and Lynn Williams on drums.<ref name="Espinoza 2020">{{cite web | last=Espinoza | first=Russ | title=Matchbox 20 And The Wallflowers Unite For 50-Date Summer Tour | website=Forbes | date=January 13, 2020 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/russespinoza/2020/01/13/matchbox-20-and-the-wallflowers-unite-for-50-date-summer-tour/ | access-date=March 25, 2021}}</ref>

In May 2016, the Wallflowers' 1996 album ''Bringing Down the Horse'' was issued on vinyl for the first time in honor of the 20th anniversary of the album's release.<ref name="Rs 2016">{{cite magazine|last1=Hyman|first1=Dan|title=Jakob Dylan on Wallflowers Breakthrough LP|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/jakob-dylan-on-wallflowers-breakthrough-lp-it-wasnt-easy-20160512|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=May 17, 2016|date=May 12, 2016}}</ref> The Wallflowers was among hundreds of artists whose material was destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]],<ref name="Rosen2">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |access-date=June 28, 2019 |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> although later research showed the master tapes for ''Bringing Down the Horse'' were not actually destroyed in the fire.<ref name="Billboard 2021">{{cite magazine | title=Jakob Dylan Talks Wallflowers' 'One Headlight' | magazine=Billboard | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/9527847/the-wallflowers-one-headlight-jakob-dylan-interview | access-date=March 25, 2021}}</ref>

The band was set to undertake a North American summer tour in 2020 alongside [[Matchbox Twenty]] prior to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bilstein |first1=John |title=Matchbox Twenty Plot Sprawling North American Tour |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/matchbox-twenty-the-wallflowers-2020-tour-dates-936908/ |website=RollingStone.com |date=January 13, 2020 |publisher=Rolling Stone |access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>

===2021–present: ''Exit Wounds''===

The band's seventh studio album, ''[[Exit Wounds (The Wallflowers album)|Exit Wounds]]'', was released on July 9, 2021, on [[New West Records]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=New West Records |title=The Wallflowers - "Roots And Wings" [Audio Only]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=StPXfW6RmGw | archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211117/StPXfW6RmGw| archive-date=2021-11-17 | url-status=live|via=YouTube |publisher=New West Records |access-date=April 8, 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> With the release of the new album, Dylan would reiterate that the band's sound is an extension of his solo work, saying "There's never been one lineup that's made two records. So the constant is myself. If you think there's a sound of the Wallflowers, I'm making that with my choices in the studio and with my songs and voice".<ref name="Greiving 2021">{{cite news | last=Greiving | first=Tim | title=Jakob Dylan has always been part cowboy-troubadour, part rabbi | newspaper=Washington Post | date=July 8, 2021 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/jakob-dylan-wallflowers-exit-wounds/2021/07/08/76643ec0-d847-11eb-9bbb-37c30dcf9363_story.html | access-date=November 30, 2021}}</ref> It was produced by [[Butch Walker]] and the band announced a 53-date arena tour to promote the album (which was postponed to 2022 due to the COVID-19 pandemic).<ref name="Benitez-Eves 2021">{{cite web | last=Benitez-Eves | first=Tina | title=The Wallflowers to Release 'Exit Wounds,' the Band's First New Album in Nearly 10 Years | website=American Songwriter | date=April 9, 2021 | url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-wallflowers-to-release-exit-wounds-the-bands-first-new-album-in-nearly-10-years/ | access-date=April 9, 2021}}</ref> About writing the album, Dylan says, "I was just also writing during a time when the world felt like it was falling apart. That changes the way you address even the simplest things, because you have panic in your mind all the time. You have anxiety. And you also have hope. And it’s all in there".<ref name="Benitez-Eves 2021"/>

